# OctoAcme — Release Manager Guide

## Purpose
Define the Release Manager role and provide a detailed release process checklist to ensure smooth, predictable releases.

## Release Manager Responsibilities
- Own the release schedule and communicate timelines
- Coordinate with QA Lead for quality sign-off
- Prepare and review release notes
- Execute or oversee deployment activities
- Manage incident response and rollback procedures
- Provide stakeholder updates and post-release summaries

## Release Workflow

### Phase 1: Release Planning (1–2 weeks before release)
- [ ] Confirm which features are ready for release
- [ ] Identify any dependencies or blockers
- [ ] Schedule deployment window (if applicable)
- [ ] Create draft release notes with development team
- [ ] Plan rollback strategy and test it in staging
- [ ] Notify stakeholders of upcoming release

### Phase 2: Release Preparation (3–5 days before)
- [ ] Lock code freeze (no new commits unless critical fixes)
- [ ] Finalize release notes and documentation
- [ ] Deploy to staging environment
- [ ] Run smoke tests and user acceptance testing (UAT)
- [ ] Confirm backup/snapshot procedures
- [ ] Brief team on deployment plan and rollback procedure

### Phase 3: Pre-Release Checklist
- [ ] QA Lead confirms quality sign-off
- [ ] All acceptance criteria met and tested
- [ ] No critical or high-priority defects open
- [ ] Security scans passed
- [ ] Performance acceptable
- [ ] Release notes reviewed and approved by Product Manager
- [ ] Deployment procedures documented and tested
- [ ] Incident response team briefed
- [ ] Support team briefed on new features/changes

### Phase 4: Deployment
- [ ] Notify stakeholders of deployment start
- [ ] Execute deployment (automated or manual)
- [ ] Run post-deployment verification
- [ ] Confirm critical flows working
- [ ] Monitor for errors/issues
- [ ] Announce release to all users/stakeholders

### Phase 5: Post-Release
- [ ] Monitor key metrics and error rates for 24–48 hours
- [ ] Respond to any critical issues
- [ ] Collect user feedback
- [ ] Document any unexpected issues
- [ ] Schedule post-release retrospective

## Release Notes Template
**Release Name/Version:** [e.g., v2.3.0]
**Release Date:** [Date]
**Release Type:** [Patch/Minor/Major]

**Summary:**
Brief overview of what's new and why it matters to users.

**New Features:**
- Feature 1: [description]
- Feature 2: [description]

**Improvements:**
- Improvement 1: [description]
- Performance: [details if applicable]

**Bug Fixes:**
- Fixed: [description]

**Known Issues:**
- [Known limitation or workaround]

**Migration/Upgrade Steps:**
[If applicable, step-by-step instructions]

**Support & Questions:**
[Contact or escalation path]

## Rollback Procedures
If a release causes critical issues:
1. Declare incident and notify on-call team
2. Assess severity and impact
3. Decide: hot-fix or rollback
4. Execute rollback to last known-good version
5. Communicate status to stakeholders
6. Schedule incident post-mortem
7. Plan fix for next release

## Go/No-Go Decision Criteria
**Go:** Proceed with release if:
- ✅ QA Lead confirms quality sign-off
- ✅ All acceptance criteria met
- ✅ No critical/high-priority defects
- ✅ Security and performance acceptable
- ✅ Release notes complete and accurate
- ✅ Deployment procedure tested

**No-Go:** Hold release if:
- ❌ Critical defects remain unfixed
- ❌ Security vulnerabilities identified
- ❌ Performance unacceptable
- ❌ Key feature incomplete or untested
- ❌ Stakeholder approval missing